<font color="#FF0000">MORE TO CLASS LASS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct  9 23:56:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass, a few additional coments:<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&quot;The posts on this site are rather disturbing to me. Not because of the language (which has sunk to an all time low) but the lack of tolerance which I thought Vietnam vets were trying to work toward and generally bend over backwards amongst ourselves to live.&quot; <br><br>
Tolerance is a two way street. What I see more frequently than not is an attitude on the part of non-vets to expect vets to behave in a &quot;certain&quot; manner. Unfortunately, this lack of latitude does not validate the state of mind of the vet, and you have a disconnect. Vietnam Vets, for the most part, were *in* the war, and were shot at. This alone will forge philosophy and attitude that can be unsettling to many. Because this society chose not to return to the vets that which was lost, I do not feel that anyone should complain when faced with a 'NamVet attitude. Some of those who fought *around* the war have difficulty in accepting this. To get a feel of what I mean, one need but to sit in the lobby of any major VA Hospital for a few days, and look and listen. You will begin to understand the nature of the vets with which you are dealing. <br><br>
You also said:<br><br>
&quot;Art, what you have written in the past shows depth, this tangent is beneath you.&quot; <br><br>
I disagree. Actually, the position I took shows a great deal of depth and understanding of the real issues. The issues were about form, rather than style or content. I was provoked. Provoke me, and the consequences flow. I do not care if people post or not, such is their perogative. I am offended by unprovoked personal attacks and outrageous unacceptable behavior, and I will react. Such things have no place anywhere. Toss in all the non sequitur stuff, and you have a real donneybrook brewing.<br><br>
Actually, I feel vindicated. 
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


